What is AWS WAF?
AWS WAF (Web Application Firewall) protects web applications from:

SQL Injection

Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)

Malicious bots

IP-based attacks

Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS) attacks

It works by inspecting incoming HTTP requests and evaluating them against rules in a Web ACL (Access Control List)





Where Can You Attach AWS WAF?

You can associate it with:

Amazon CloudFront

Application Load Balancer

Amazon API Gateway





Step 1️⃣ Deploy Sample Web App on EC2

Use:

Amazon EC2

Quick setup:

sudo yum update -y
sudo yum install httpd -y
sudo systemctl start httpd
echo "Welcome to My Secure Web App - Day 2" | sudo tee /var/www/html/





Step 2️⃣ Create Web ACL in AWS WAF

Go to AWS Console → WAF

Create Web ACL

Choose Region

Add rules:

Recommended Managed Rules:

AWS Managed SQL Injection Rule

AWS Managed Common Rule Set

IP Reputation List

Step 3️⃣ Add Custom Rule (Example)

Block specific IP:

Rule type: IP set

Action: Block

OR block SQL pattern:

SELECT * FROM






Step 4️⃣ Associate Web ACL

Attach to:

ALB (recommended for beginners)

OR

CloudFront (if globally distributed app)

Step 5️⃣ Test It

Try visiting your website with:

http://your-ip/?id=1' OR '1'='1



